Bellabeat Case Study¶

I am tasked with uncovering trends within fitness tracker usage, and applying those trends to the marketing of a Bellabeat product.

About Fitness Trackers¶

Fitness tracking is a growing market, valued at $53.94 billion in 2023 and projected to reach $290.85 billion by 2032. Smartwatch users in the US increased from 21.19 million in 2017 to 39.92 million in 2020[2]. There is a shift toward smartwatches, as they provide music streaming, mobile payments, notifications and other features that strict fitness trackers lack[1]. Fitness trackers are incorporating more advanced health monitoring capabilities, including: blood pressure monitoring, blood oxygen level tracking,stress level measurement, sleep apnea detection, and ECG capabilities[2][3] Artificial intelligence is being integrated to provide more personalized health insights and recommendations based on collected data[2]. There's an increased focus on real-time data analysis and customized guidance for diet, exercise, and recovery[2]. Manufacturers are prioritizing stylish and fashionable designs to make fitness trackers more appealing as everyday accessories[3]. Fitness trackers are increasingly being integrated with other IoT devices and health apps for a more comprehensive health management approach[3]. Given the prevalence of chronic diseases, there's growing interest in using these devices in clinical settings and research programs to collect real-time patient data[4]. Some companies are developing trackers specifically focused on women's health, addressing unique health monitoring needs[4].

These trends indicate a shift towards more sophisticated, multi-functional, and stylish fitness tracking devices that offer comprehensive health monitoring and integrate seamlessly with users' lifestyles and broader health management systems.

Why Buy Wearables¶

Wearables are purchased in the US to track daily activity(43%), monitor health(31%), track exercise(29%), to access smartphone capabilities(25%), to track sleep(19%), to connect socially(13%), and to access safety related functionality(13%)[1].

[1] https://www.statista.com/statistics/1351144/top-reasons-for-buying-wearables-us/

About Bellabeat¶

The results of the following summary of reviews are not as reliable as a user survey. Many findings are singular; they may not be indicative of general product performance. Nonetheless, this research gives a starting point to understanding the Bellabeat Leaf and app.

Overall Impression¶

The Leaf and Leaf Urban are generally well-received for their unique design and focus on women's health. However, there are some mixed reviews regarding functionality and durability.

Pros¶

The Leaf is widely praised for its stylish and versatile design[1][2][4]. It is considered genuinely fashionable, not just "not ugly"[4]. Many users appreciate menstrual cycle tracking[3][4][5]. The app also offers pregnancy tracking and considers breastfeeding as a calorie-burning activity[5]. The Leaf and app track activity, sleep, and breathing exercises[4][5]. Users appreciate how discreet the device is[1][3].

Cons¶

Some users report inaccuracies in sleep and exercise tracking[1][3]. Another had devices that stopped working after 1.5-2 years[1]. Some dislike the lack of display on the device itself, and the lack of heart rate monitoring and calorie counting features[4]. According to one review, the battery needs replacement more frequently than claimed (about every 3 months)[1]. 2 reviews mentioned that it is easy to forget to wear the device[1][3].

  • [1] https://thingtesting.com/brands/bellabeat/reviews

  • [4] https://www.pcmag.com/reviews/bellabeat-leaf
  • [5] https://www.pcmag.com/reviews/bellabeat-leaf-urban

Summary¶

Bellabeat products are appreciated for their design and women-specific features, but there's room for improvement in accuracy, durability, and advanced tracking capabilities. Bellabeat targets a niche but growing market of women who are interested in a more discreet, stylish tracking solution than the smartwatch trend. To remain competitive, Bellabeat will likely have to integrate more realtime data analytics and AI into its app.

Analysis¶

Bellabeat sells several items, but they all integrate with the app. The app tracks activity and sleep, among other things. Our dataset contains observations on activity and sleep, so this analysis focusses there.

Dataset Quality¶

  • Somewhat Reliable: The data comes from amazon mechanical turk, so it may contain errors. The data has a relatively small sample size–33 is the max and mode- which makes it unrepresentative of the total North American market.
  • Not Original: The data was collected for a third party, it doesn't come from Bellabeat itself.
  • Not Comprehensive: The data lacks demographic information.
  • Not Current: Our data is from 2016, which is 8 years out of date. Certain Fitbit metrics like VeryActiveMinutes are now deprecated.
  • Cited: the dataset is also stored at zenodo, which has been cited here, as citation 64.

Despite the low quality, fitness and usage trends in the data are likely still relevant.

Out[12]:
<Axes: xlabel='Hour of Day', ylabel='Average, Normalized Activity'>

All measures except sleep, when normalized, follow almost exactly the same path, peaking at 12pm-2pm and again at 5pm-7pm. It appears that people are getting their exercise in the afternoon, especially at lunch and directly after work. Conversely, they are relatively inactive in the morning and evening.

Bellabeat can send their users notifications during or before peak activity to increase motivation and engagement. They can also encourage appropriate activities during low-activity times. Meditation would be a great choice, since the Leaf tracks it. If Bellabeat has these features, they could advertise that they are sensitive to users energy levels throughout the day.

In [14]:
ggplot(dailyActivity, aes(x='TotalSteps')) + geom_histogram() + labs(title='Total Steps', x='Total Steps Per Day', y='Count')

There are a large number of days with zero steps, which is likely because users aren't wearing their tracker. One Bellabeat review mentioned forgetting to wear as a problem with the Bellabeat Leaf. To counteract this, if Bellabeat detects a high number of zero step days, it could mention this in app, asking if the user is wearing their tracker and reminding them of the benefits of being aware of how many steps they are taking.

Most days get 7000 to 8000 steps, which, though slightly less than the popular 10,000 step goal, is still healthy. Bellabeat can encourage users to set this as a goal when they are getting close to it, reminding them that it is a health marker too. It may not be an effective goal for lower activity days/users, as they might not feel like they can make it. For some more active users, knowing the average may actually be demotivating, unless they are the competitive type.

With these features, Bellabeat can market that it takes an individual and health oriented perspective on activity, customizing suggestions for each user.

We see two groups in these graphs: those with more than a 1000 sedentary minutes (16 hours) and those with less than that.

Those in the more sedentary category likely have desk jobs, while those in the other group do not. If the category split was due to athleticism or having an excersise routine, lower sedentary minutes would correlate more strongly with total steps. If it were due to health, the segmentation would be more graded. If it were a weekend/weekday split, day of week faceting would reveal the trend.

Bellabeat can segment their campaigns based on activity class.

  • Active users may be interested in tracking caloric burn and seeing how their daily activity contributes to overall fitness. They may also be reminded that just because they are less sedentary doesn't mean they are necessarily burning more calories or taking more steps.
  • More sedentary users could use movement reminders after prolonged sitting.

If they offer segmented advice, Bellabeat can advertise that they personalize their results based on activity level and other metrics.

Sleep¶

It's unclear what minuteSleep is measuring, since it peaks during the afternoon at 12 pm and 5 pm. For further analysis we will consider the sleep day data.

In general, people sleep 7-8 hours a night. Some users get significantly less than this on some days, and some users appear to catch up on Friday and the weekend, sleeping more those days.

People know that sleep is important for health and that you need 7-8 hours of sleep a day on average. The first graph shows that most people accomplish this. However, it's lesser known that high sleep variability is linked to cognitive decline. The second graph shows that a lot of people have somewhat high sleep variability.

Because it tracks sleep habits, Bellabeat's Leaf can encourage users with higher sleep variability to become more consistent. We can market the product based on this benefit.

In general, sleep time matches time in bed. However, on a subset of nights, some people spend more than 85 minutes in bed not sleeping, meaning that they are likely having trouble sleeping. Bellabeat can market to this subset of people, showing that Bellabeat's sleep tracker can monitor sleep quality and suggest ways to improve it (less caffeine and alcohol for example) when it isn't great. It can also help identify users with chronic sleep problems.

Marketing Insights for Bellabeat¶

1. Daily Activity Patterns¶

  • Insight: Activity peaks midday and in the evening, with low activity in the early morning and night.
  • Action: Bellabeat could boost engagement by sending motivational reminders before peak times and suggesting low-intensity activities during less active periods (e.g., morning yoga, evening meditation).
  • Marketing Angle: Promote Bellabeat’s sensitivity to users' daily energy, positioning it as a supportive partner in both active and restful times.

2. Step Trends¶

  • Insight: Users average around 7,000–8,000 steps, slightly below the 10,000-step benchmark. Days with zero steps likely reflect non-tracker usage.
  • Action: Encourage users to set achievable step goals close to their average to maintain motivation, with gentle nudges reminding them of tracker benefits.
  • Marketing Angle: Highlight Bellabeat’s encouragement strategy for personalized, attainable activity goals.

3. Sedentary Minutes¶

  • Insight: Users fall into two distinct groups: those with more than 1,000 sedentary minutes (likely desk jobs) and those with less.
  • Action: Segment campaigns by user activity level:
    • Active Users: Highlight caloric tracking and fitness progress.
    • Sedentary Users: Promote movement reminders to reduce prolonged sitting times.
  • Marketing Angle: Emphasize Bellabeat’s ability to personalize recommendations based on activity levels, catering to different lifestyles.

4. Sleep Patterns¶

  • Insight: Most users get the recommended 7-8 hours, though many exhibit high sleep variability, which can negatively impact cognitive health.
  • Action: Promote consistency to users with high sleep variability and address those with frequent sleep disruptions with practical sleep-quality tips (e.g., reduced caffeine/alcohol).
  • Marketing Angle: Market Bellabeat as a tool for achieving consistent, high-quality sleep, with added benefits of identifying and addressing sleep challenges over time.

These insights position Bellabeat as a supportive and personalized wellness solution, with targeted marketing to users based on individual routines, needs, and health priorities.
